```cpp
inline string_t Extract(const string_t &input, Vector &result, const RE2 &re, const duckdb_re2::StringPiece &rewrite) {
    string extracted;
    RE2::Extract(input.GetString(), re, rewrite, &extracted);
    return StringVector::AddString(result, extracted.c_str(), extracted.size());
}
```

Copy this exactly: build your output in a `std::string` (or any owned buffer), then `StringVector::AddString(result, ptr, len)`. The returned `string_t` is owned by the result Vector's heap, so it stays alive for the lifetime of the output chunk. **Crucially** — `StringVector::AddString` takes `result` (the output `Vector &`), not the input. Returning a raw `string_t` pointing at stack memory would be a use-after-free.

