**`/Users/tim_vergenz/code/personal/duckdb-jq/duckdb/src/function/scalar/string/nfc_normalize.cpp:9`**:

```cpp
struct NFCNormalizeOperator {
    template <class INPUT_TYPE, class RESULT_TYPE>
    static RESULT_TYPE Operation(INPUT_TYPE input, Vector &result) {
        auto input_data = input.GetData();
        auto input_length = input.GetSize();
        if (IsAscii(input_data, input_length)) {
            return input;                                        // pass-through, no copy
        }
        auto normalized_str = Utf8Proc::Normalize(input_data, input_length);
        auto result_str = StringVector::AddString(result, normalized_str);
        free(normalized_str);
        return result_str;
    }
};
void NFCNormalizeFunction(DataChunk &args, ExpressionState &state, Vector &result) {
    UnaryExecutor::ExecuteString<string_t, string_t, NFCNormalizeOperator>(args.data[0], result, args.size());
    StringVector::AddHeapReference(result, args.data[0]);
}
```

Two notes worth copying:
- `return input;` — when no transformation occurs you can return the input `string_t` directly (zero-copy pass-through). Pair with `StringVector::AddHeapReference(result, args.data[0])` to keep the source heap alive for the duration of the result. Useful for jq's `.` identity filter.
- `StringVector::AddString` accepts either a `const char*` (null-terminated), a `(const char*, idx_t)` pair, or a `std::string`. For binary-safe data (could contain `\0`), use the explicit length overload — same name, `StringVector::AddStringOrBlob` is only needed for the BLOB type.

### 4c. Even closer — the JSON extension's pattern (returning `string_t` directly from a buffer)

**`/Users/tim_vergenz/code/personal/duckdb-jq/duckdb/extension/json/json_functions/json_pretty.cpp:6`**:

```cpp
string_t PrettyPrint(yyjson_val *val, yyjson_alc *alc, Vector &, ValidityMask &, idx_t) {
    size_t len_size_t;
    auto data = yyjson_val_write_opts(val, JSONCommon::WRITE_PRETTY_FLAG, alc, &len_size_t, nullptr);
    idx_t len = len_size_t;
    return string_t(data, len);
}
```

Note this constructs a `string_t` from `(data, len)` **without** going through `StringVector::AddString` — only legal because `alc` (the yyjson allocator) is itself bound to the result vector via `JSONAllocator::AddBuffer(result, alc)` after the loop. The simpler/safer pattern for jq is the `StringVector::AddString(result, ...)` route in 4a/4b; only adopt the allocator-attached pattern if you have a per-chunk arena you want to own. The JSON extension uses one because it's allocating many tiny strings per row and wants to amortize.

